Report: act_report¶

We Rate Dogs : Analysis and Visualization of Tweet Archive of Twitter User @dog_rates, also known as WeRateDogs¶

Analysis, communication and insights of tweet archive data of Twitter user @dog_rates, also known as WeRateDogs using jupyter notebooks, python and its libraries such as matplotlib.

Gathered Data¶

Data for my analysis and visualization was gathered from three (3) different sources. The sources include:

  1. Twitter archive file was manually downloaded from a local workbook stored as twitter_archive_enhanced.csv and written into a pandas dataframe df_doggo.
  1. The tweet image predictions file (image_predictions.tsv) which is hosted on Udacity's servers, was programmatically downloaded using the python Requests library and accessed using the following URL: https://d17h27t6h515a5.cloudfront.net/topher/2017/August/599fd2ad_image-predictions/image-predictions.tsv. This was file was then written into a pandas dataframe twitter_image_prediction.
  1. Json data was gathered/read from a tweet_json.txt file line by line, generated by udacity using the tweet IDs in the WeRateDogs Twitter archive, employing Twitter API to query each tweet's JSON data. The gathered data was read into a pandas dataframe my_tweet_json with minimum columns of tweet_id, retweet_count, favorite_count.

Assessed Data¶

The data gathered for my analysis was visually and programmatically assessed. Eight issues had to do with the quality of the data and two issues had to do with the tidiness and structure of the data to be used for analysis and visualization. Issues documented included :

Quality

  1. Some columns are not useful for analysis in df_doggo dataset.

  2. Datatype of timestamp column is not correct.

  3. One column consisting of day, month , and year for the timestamp.

  4. Data of doggo, floofer, pupper and puppo columns are not under one column.

  5. Some columns have non-available or null data.

  6. Too many columns to present image dog prediction.

  7. Some columns are not useful in my analysis in twitter_image_predict.

  8. Column 'id' name should be 'tweet_id'.

Tidiness

  1. A column for computed rating not available.
  2. All the 3 tables are not in one dataset for analysis and visualization.

Cleaned and Stored data¶

The assessed data and issues were cleaned and stored into new datasets df_doggo_clean, twitter_image_predict_clean, my_tweet_json_clean. These data set were then merged to form one dataset/dataframe called the twitter_archive_master. This dataframe was subsequently used for analysis and visualization.

twitter_archive_master : Final dataframe for analysis and visualization.

Analysis, Visualization and Insights¶

Three insights were documented/ concluded based on analysis and visualization. The insights are as follows:

Insight 1. Japanese spaniel has the lowest average dog rating and clumber has the highest dog rating.

Insight 2. The golden retriever was the most common dog rated in the master dataset followed by labrador retriever.

Insight 3. Predicted dog types with low rating counts showed low average ratings.

Insight 4. Saluki and Brabancon_griffon had the highest and lowest average favorite counts respectively, for all the predicted dog types.

Insight 1¶

For my first insight, the predicted dog types were sorted out based on the mean of their final rating to show the minimum and maximum ratings.

To do this, the predicted dog type was initially grouped according to their mean and sorted out to show the highest mean and lowest mean ratings.

From the analysis in the code below, it shows that the Japanese spaniel has the lowest mean rating while the clumber dog type recorded the highest mean rating.

Insight 3¶

For my last insight, the predicted dog types were grouped according to the mean of their final ratings and assigned to the variable dog_predict_rating_average. The predicted dog types were grouped again according to the counts of their final ratings and assigned to the variable dog_predict_rating_count. A dataframe was created and the data from assigned variables were appended. Insight three was further visualized using scatter plot, to show how the average final ratings of the predicted dog types varied with the final rating counts of predicted dog types.
